# tuple - Rust

## Primitive Type [tuple](#)

1.0.0 Â·

Expand description

A finite heterogeneous sequence, `(T, U, ..)`.

Letâ€™s cover each of those in turn:

Tuples are _finite_. In other words, a tuple has a length. Hereâ€™s a tuple of length `3`:

â€˜Lengthâ€™ is also sometimes called â€˜arityâ€™ here; each tuple of a different length is a different, distinct type.

Tuples are _heterogeneous_. This means that each element of the tuple can have a different type. In that tuple above, it has the type:

```
(&'static str, i32, char)
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+_:%0A++++(%26%27static+str,+i32,+char)%0A++++=+(%22hello%22,+5,+%27c%27);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Tuples are a _sequence_. This means that they can be accessed by position; this is called â€˜tuple indexingâ€™, and it looks like this:

```
let tuple = ("hello", 5, 'c');

assert_eq!(tuple.0, "hello");
assert_eq!(tuple.1, 5);
assert_eq!(tuple.2, 'c');
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+tuple+=+(%22hello%22,+5,+%27c%27);%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(tuple.0,+%22hello%22);%0A++++assert_eq!(tuple.1,+5);%0A++++assert_eq!(tuple.2,+%27c%27);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

The sequential nature of the tuple applies to its implementations of various traits. For example, in [`PartialOrd`](cmp/trait.PartialOrd.html "trait std::cmp::PartialOrd") and [`Ord`](cmp/trait.Ord.html "trait std::cmp::Ord"), the elements are compared sequentially until the first non-equal set is found.

For more about tuples, see [the book](about:blank/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#the-tuple-type).

## [Â§](#trait-implementations-1)Trait implementations

In this documentation the shorthand `(Tâ‚, Tâ‚‚, â€¦, Tâ‚™)` is used to represent tuples of varying length. When that is used, any trait bound expressed on `T` applies to each element of the tuple independently. Note that this is a convenience notation to avoid repetitive documentation, not valid Rust syntax.

Due to a temporary restriction in Rustâ€™s type system, the following traits are only implemented on tuples of arity 12 or less. In the future, this may change:

-   [`PartialEq`](cmp/trait.PartialEq.html "trait std::cmp::PartialEq")
-   [`Eq`](cmp/trait.Eq.html "trait std::cmp::Eq")
-   [`PartialOrd`](cmp/trait.PartialOrd.html "trait std::cmp::PartialOrd")
-   [`Ord`](cmp/trait.Ord.html "trait std::cmp::Ord")
-   [`Debug`](fmt/trait.Debug.html "trait std::fmt::Debug")
-   [`Default`](default/trait.Default.html "trait std::default::Default")
-   [`Hash`](hash/trait.Hash.html "trait std::hash::Hash")
-   [`From<[T; N]>`](convert/trait.From.html "trait std::convert::From")

The following traits are implemented for tuples of any length. These traits have implementations that are automatically generated by the compiler, so are not limited by missing language features.

-   [`Clone`](clone/trait.Clone.html "trait std::clone::Clone")
-   [`Copy`](marker/trait.Copy.html "trait std::marker::Copy")
-   [`Send`](marker/trait.Send.html "trait std::marker::Send")
-   [`Sync`](marker/trait.Sync.html "trait std::marker::Sync")
-   [`Unpin`](marker/trait.Unpin.html "trait std::marker::Unpin")
-   [`UnwindSafe`](panic/trait.UnwindSafe.html "trait std::panic::UnwindSafe")
-   [`RefUnwindSafe`](panic/trait.RefUnwindSafe.html "trait std::panic::RefUnwindSafe")

## [Â§](#examples)Examples

Basic usage:

```
let tuple = ("hello", 5, 'c');

assert_eq!(tuple.0, "hello");
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+tuple+=+(%22hello%22,+5,+%27c%27);%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(tuple.0,+%22hello%22);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Tuples are often used as a return type when you want to return more than one value:

```
fn calculate_point() -> (i32, i32) {
    // Don't do a calculation, that's not the point of the example
    (4, 5)
}

let point = calculate_point();

assert_eq!(point.0, 4);
assert_eq!(point.1, 5);

// Combining this with patterns can be nicer.

let (x, y) = calculate_point();

assert_eq!(x, 4);
assert_eq!(y, 5);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++fn+calculate_point()+-%3E+(i32,+i32)+%7B%0A++++++++//+Don%27t+do+a+calculation,+that%27s+not+the+point+of+the+example%0A++++++++(4,+5)%0A++++%7D%0A++++%0A++++let+point+=+calculate_point();%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(point.0,+4);%0A++++assert_eq!(point.1,+5);%0A++++%0A++++//+Combining+this+with+patterns+can+be+nicer.%0A++++%0A++++let+(x,+y)+=+calculate_point();%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(x,+4);%0A++++assert_eq!(y,+5);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Homogeneous tuples can be created from arrays of appropriate length:

```
let array: [u32; 3] = [1, 2, 3];
let tuple: (u32, u32, u32) = array.into();
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+array:+%5Bu32;+3%5D+=+%5B1,+2,+3%5D;%0A++++let+tuple:+(u32,+u32,+u32)+=+array.into();%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Allows to `extend` a tuple of collections that also implement `Extend`.

See also: [`Iterator::unzip`](about:blank/iter/trait.Iterator.html#method.unzip "method std::iter::Iterator::unzip")

##### [Â§](#examples-1)Examples

```
let mut tuple = (vec![0], vec![1]);
tuple.extend([(2, 3), (4, 5), (6, 7)]);
assert_eq!(tuple.0, [0, 2, 4, 6]);
assert_eq!(tuple.1, [1, 3, 5, 7]);

// also allows for arbitrarily nested tuples as elements
let mut nested_tuple = (vec![1], (vec![2], vec![3]));
nested_tuple.extend([(4, (5, 6)), (7, (8, 9))]);

let (a, (b, c)) = nested_tuple;
assert_eq!(a, [1, 4, 7]);
assert_eq!(b, [2, 5, 8]);
assert_eq!(c, [3, 6, 9]);
```

This implementation turns an iterator of tuples into a tuple of types which implement [`Default`](default/trait.Default.html "trait std::default::Default") and [`Extend`](iter/trait.Extend.html "trait std::iter::Extend").

This is similar to [`Iterator::unzip`](about:blank/iter/trait.Iterator.html#method.unzip "method std::iter::Iterator::unzip"), but is also composable with other [`FromIterator`](iter/trait.FromIterator.html "trait std::iter::FromIterator") implementations:

```
let string = "1,2,123,4";

let (numbers, lengths): (Vec<_>, Vec<_>) = string
    .split(',')
    .map(|s| s.parse().map(|n: u32| (n, s.len())))
```

Expand description

A finite heterogeneous sequence, (T, U, ..).

Letâ€™s cover each of those in turn:

Tuples are finite. In other words, a tuple has a length. Hereâ€™s a tuple of length 3:

("hello", 5, 'c');
Run

â€˜Lengthâ€™ is also sometimes called â€˜arityâ€™ here; each tuple of a different length is a different, distinct type.

Tuples are heterogeneous. This means that each element of the tuple can have a different type. In that tuple above, it has the type:

(&'static str, i32, char)
Run

Tuples are a sequence. This means that they can be accessed by position; this is called â€˜tuple indexingâ€™, and it looks like this:

let tuple = ("hello", 5, 'c');

assert_eq!(tuple.0, "hello");
assert_eq!(tuple.1, 5);
assert_eq!(tuple.2, 'c');
Run

The sequential nature of the tuple applies to its implementations of various traits. For example, in PartialOrd and Ord, the elements are compared sequentially until the first non-equal set is found.

For more about tuples, see the book.

Â§Trait implementations

In this documentation the shorthand (Tâ‚, Tâ‚‚, â€¦, Tâ‚™) is used to represent tuples of varying length. When that is used, any trait bound expressed on T applies to each element of the tuple independently. Note that this is a convenience notation to avoid repetitive documentation, not valid Rust syntax.

Due to a temporary restriction in Rustâ€™s type system, the following traits are only implemented on tuples of arity 12 or less. In the future, this may change:

  • PartialEq
  • Eq
  • PartialOrd
  • Ord
  • Debug
  • Default
  • Hash
  • From<[T; N]>

The following traits are implemented for tuples of any length. These traits have implementations that are automatically generated by the compiler, so are not limited by missing language features.

  • Clone
  • Copy
  • Send
  • Sync
  • Unpin
  • UnwindSafe
  • RefUnwindSafe

Â§Examples

Basic usage:

let tuple = ("hello", 5, 'c');

assert_eq!(tuple.0, "hello");
Run

Tuples are often used as a return type when you want to return more than one value:

fn calculate_point() -> (i32, i32) {
    // Don't do a calculation, that's not the point of the example
    (4, 5)
}

let point = calculate_point();

assert_eq!(point.0, 4);
assert_eq!(point.1, 5);

// Combining this with patterns can be nicer.

let (x, y) = calculate_point();

assert_eq!(x, 4);
assert_eq!(y, 5);
Run

Homogeneous tuples can be created from arrays of appropriate length:

let array: [u32; 3] = [1, 2, 3];
let tuple: (u32, u32, u32) = array.into();
Run
